WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.060 --> 00:00:01.060
&gt;&gt;JACKIE FAHERTY: Is everybody excited?

00:00:01.060 --> 00:00:03.800
I’m just going to start with that.

00:00:03.800 --> 00:00:12.120
That’s good, because I can guarantee you
have never seen the Milky Way like you’re

00:00:12.120 --> 00:00:13.620
about to see it tonight.

00:00:13.620 --> 00:00:16.590
And it’s in part—that was a scream, I
like it.

00:00:16.590 --> 00:00:20.029
Whatever this energy is, I’m going to work
with it.

00:00:20.029 --> 00:00:27.480
What you’re going to see is rendering of
data that we do here at the American Museum

00:00:27.480 --> 00:00:28.550
of Natural History.

00:00:28.550 --> 00:00:34.180
And I’m so excited to show it to you because—I
mean, you guys are going to be some of the

00:00:34.180 --> 00:00:41.800
first people to see data in this way, rendered
in this kind of way because you are here in

00:00:41.800 --> 00:00:45.600
this place at the American Museum of Natural
History where we have some of the best data

00:00:45.600 --> 00:00:46.600
visualization tools.

00:00:46.600 --> 00:00:47.600
All right, so.

00:00:47.600 --> 00:00:51.120
To start, I want to set the landscape for
you.

00:00:51.120 --> 00:00:53.550
The landscape of astronomy.

00:00:53.550 --> 00:01:00.870
This is a picture of the nighttime sky, it’s
about the best kind of nighttime sky anybody

00:01:00.870 --> 00:01:04.210
on this Earth could hope to see.

00:01:04.210 --> 00:01:06.090
This is a picture of the nighttime sky.

00:01:06.090 --> 00:01:10.540
I was actually inside of one of those telescopes
when this picture was taken.

00:01:10.540 --> 00:01:15.979
This is a picture taken from the Las Campanas
Observatory, which is in northern Chile.

00:01:15.979 --> 00:01:21.280
And you’re seeing a fairly realistic, just
a little bit heightened, beautified image,

00:01:21.280 --> 00:01:24.509
of what the nighttime sky should really look
like.

00:01:24.509 --> 00:01:26.090
This is actually a very special picture.

00:01:26.090 --> 00:01:28.460
This was actually on my birthday a couple
of years ago.

00:01:28.460 --> 00:01:31.909
The photographer, Yuri Beletsky, took it for
me while I was observing.

00:01:31.909 --> 00:01:35.429
Notice there’s this red dot on the upper
right-hand side, I don’t know if you guys

00:01:35.429 --> 00:01:36.429
can notice that.

00:01:36.429 --> 00:01:39.150
It was a total lunar eclipse this night.

00:01:39.150 --> 00:01:40.659
So, actually—yeah, I like this.

00:01:40.659 --> 00:01:41.659
You guys, very nice, very nice, you’re into
it.

00:01:41.659 --> 00:01:44.090
On the left-hand side you’re seeing the
large and small Magellanic Clouds.

00:01:44.090 --> 00:01:48.670
You can tell it’s the southern hemisphere
if you’re seeing those two satellite galaxies

00:01:48.670 --> 00:01:50.319
of the Milky Way.

00:01:50.319 --> 00:01:54.429
And this picture, to me, I’ve got a giant
version of this up in my office.

00:01:54.429 --> 00:01:56.469
It’s one of my favorite pictures taken.

00:01:56.469 --> 00:01:59.170
And it is a gorgeous view.

00:01:59.170 --> 00:02:03.259
This is the view of the nighttime sky and
so when I ask all of you what you think of

00:02:03.259 --> 00:02:07.750
when you think of the cosmos, you probably
think of the nighttime sky.

00:02:07.750 --> 00:02:13.189
And you’d probably want to think of the
nighttime sky that I’ve got pictured for

00:02:13.189 --> 00:02:14.489
you here.

00:02:14.489 --> 00:02:21.319
However, and this is a beautiful image, you’re
missing some critical information here.

00:02:21.319 --> 00:02:30.100
The critical information that humans are just
not capable of detecting is how far away all

00:02:30.100 --> 00:02:31.900
this stuff is.

00:02:31.900 --> 00:02:33.720
Your eyes can’t tell that.

00:02:33.720 --> 00:02:38.280
You can’t tell that those two galaxies are
galaxies.

00:02:38.280 --> 00:02:41.639
That they’re not inside of the Milky Way
that we live in.

00:02:41.639 --> 00:02:42.959
You can’t tell that.

00:02:42.959 --> 00:02:47.870
You can’t tell what in this picture is the
closest star to you.

00:02:47.870 --> 00:02:49.329
You can’t see that.

00:02:49.329 --> 00:02:51.620
You actually need something else.

00:02:51.620 --> 00:02:57.799
You need science, which is real, not that
fake news, it’s real news.

00:02:57.799 --> 00:03:02.980
Well, with the applause on that.

00:03:02.980 --> 00:03:09.750
Science will give you answers to things like,
how far away is a star?

00:03:09.750 --> 00:03:11.959
And we’ve figured that out.

00:03:11.959 --> 00:03:16.340
The other thing that you don’t get from
this image, while magical and beautiful, is

00:03:16.340 --> 00:03:20.680
you can’t see motion in this image.

00:03:20.680 --> 00:03:25.870
All of these stars, everything that’s in
this picture right now, this snapshot taken

00:03:25.870 --> 00:03:30.790
on a gorgeous night during a total lunar eclipse
in Chile, is moving.

00:03:30.790 --> 00:03:34.909
But you’re not seeing it here.

00:03:34.909 --> 00:03:39.859
And what I get to show you tonight, through
the magic of data visualization tools and

00:03:39.859 --> 00:03:46.939
the magic of science, but it’s not magic,
‘cause it’s science, is—I’m going

00:03:46.939 --> 00:03:49.239
to show you how stars move.

00:03:49.239 --> 00:03:53.290
I’m going to take time and I’m going to
turn it on for you.

00:03:53.290 --> 00:03:59.959
And I’m going to show you how we can learn
a tremendous amount about our galaxy by looking

00:03:59.959 --> 00:04:02.930
at how far away stars are and how they move.

00:04:02.930 --> 00:04:07.499
So, I’ve got several movies that will take
us through that.

00:04:07.499 --> 00:04:08.499
And I want to thank a couple of things—this
talk was made possible by a couple of things.

00:04:08.499 --> 00:04:11.999
Number one, and the reason why I can do this
tonight, and I’m sure many of you actually

00:04:11.999 --> 00:04:15.690
don’t know this because it didn’t get
the kind of press I think it should have.

00:04:15.690 --> 00:04:18.359
That’s a satellite called Gaia.

00:04:18.359 --> 00:04:21.850
Gaia was launched several years ago.

00:04:21.850 --> 00:04:28.250
And on April 25th of this year, the entire
perception of the Milky Way was changed.

00:04:28.250 --> 00:04:33.600
The entire perception of astronomy was changed
on April 25th of this year.

00:04:33.600 --> 00:04:40.880
The foundation of astrophysics—the foundation
of everything you know about the cosmos—you

00:04:40.880 --> 00:04:44.050
need to know how far away something is.

00:04:44.050 --> 00:04:45.940
You need to know how far away a star is.

00:04:45.940 --> 00:04:48.030
It’s the foundation of stellar astrophysics.

00:04:48.030 --> 00:04:52.380
It’s the foundation of cosmology, it’s
the foundation of everything.

00:04:52.380 --> 00:04:58.650
And everything we knew until April 25th, 2018
of this year, was based on a prior mission—it’s

00:04:58.650 --> 00:04:59.650
one of the trivia questions, I don’t know
if anybody got it right—a mission called

00:04:59.650 --> 00:05:00.650
Hipparcos.

00:05:00.650 --> 00:05:05.849
There were 120,000 stars that Hipparcos had
measured distances from.

00:05:05.849 --> 00:05:10.890
And then we extrapolated on that and got a
ton of new information.

00:05:10.890 --> 00:05:19.180
Gaia came out on April 25th and released 1.7
billion parallaxes—distances to stars and

00:05:19.180 --> 00:05:20.180
motion.

00:05:20.180 --> 00:05:24.480
A hundred and twenty-thousand is what modern
astrophysics was based upon.

00:05:24.480 --> 00:05:27.970
One-point-seven billion is what we got on
April 25th.

00:05:27.970 --> 00:05:29.260
So that’s a big difference.

00:05:29.260 --> 00:05:34.330
You can applaud Gaia, because it is an amazing
mission.

00:05:34.330 --> 00:05:40.990
So, what I’m going to do for you is I’m
taking subsets of that Gaia data, and anytime

00:05:40.990 --> 00:05:44.500
you want to see Gaia, come to something we
do upstairs in the dome.

00:05:44.500 --> 00:05:46.950
I can fly you through 900 million stars.

00:05:46.950 --> 00:05:49.510
No one on this planet has seen that unless
you’ve seen it here, just FYI.

00:05:49.510 --> 00:05:50.510
The other thing, I’m using three pieces
of software throughout.

00:05:50.510 --> 00:05:51.510
You’ll note, I’ll have a little note on
the bottom of my screen during the movie so

00:05:51.510 --> 00:05:52.510
you can see which piece of software I’m
using.

00:05:52.510 --> 00:05:53.510
Some of this we develop here.

00:05:53.510 --> 00:05:54.510
Some of the movies you’ll see that it’s
me rendering them as I work through the science.

00:05:54.510 --> 00:05:55.820
But I’m going to take the Gaia dataset,
I’m going to break it down into subsets,

00:05:55.820 --> 00:06:00.180
and I’m going to explain to you how science
has moved forward using this amazing dataset

00:06:00.180 --> 00:06:01.509
with data visualization tools.

00:06:01.509 --> 00:06:06.720
So, I’m going to start with—I just showed
you the Milky Way.

00:06:06.720 --> 00:06:12.750
And there’s—this is going to be a movie
that I made using Partiview software, an open

00:06:12.750 --> 00:06:15.229
source piece of software.

00:06:15.229 --> 00:06:19.910
And this is a subset—so, 1.7 billion stars
breaks a laptop.

00:06:19.910 --> 00:06:20.910
So.

00:06:20.910 --> 00:06:26.060
Just in case you were wondering, it’s very
hard to render that on your laptop.

00:06:26.060 --> 00:06:27.470
So I’m going to show you subsets.

00:06:27.470 --> 00:06:29.759
This is going to be a couple hundred thousand
stars.

00:06:29.759 --> 00:06:30.759
A couple hundred thousand.

00:06:30.759 --> 00:06:33.430
It’s like me rolling my eyes at that—that’s
amazing.

00:06:33.430 --> 00:06:35.220
A couple hundred thousand stars.

00:06:35.220 --> 00:06:36.650
I’m going to run through this.

00:06:36.650 --> 00:06:40.470
So, this, now, is—this is not an image.

00:06:40.470 --> 00:06:42.110
These are all dots.

00:06:42.110 --> 00:06:46.040
These are all stars for which we’ve measured
the positions.

00:06:46.040 --> 00:06:51.690
And already you can see, before I start the
movie, it looks like the Milky Way already.

00:06:51.690 --> 00:06:53.629
I call this pointillism.

00:06:53.629 --> 00:06:56.360
It’s pointillism of the Milky Way galaxy.

00:06:56.360 --> 00:06:58.280
No one has ever been able to do this before.

00:06:58.280 --> 00:07:03.710
I’m going to turn this on and you’re going
to see—this is my flying around in the data.

00:07:03.710 --> 00:07:06.770
It’s a screenshot of me, using the software.

00:07:06.770 --> 00:07:10.930
And so the best part of this now is I can
fly out.

00:07:10.930 --> 00:07:13.150
I can actually move outside of the data.

00:07:13.150 --> 00:07:15.139
This is a specific subset of data.

00:07:15.139 --> 00:07:17.659
These are the hottest stars.

00:07:17.659 --> 00:07:21.710
So we never knew exactly how far away they
were because no one could actually measure

00:07:21.710 --> 00:07:25.349
their distances before, we didn’t actually
have a satellite that could do it.

00:07:25.349 --> 00:07:27.610
You can see I’m rendering this, I’m moving
out.

00:07:27.610 --> 00:07:33.540
So these are what are called the O and the
B stars that live hard, die fast.

00:07:33.540 --> 00:07:37.759
There’s like a—I mean, that’s literally
what happens.

00:07:37.759 --> 00:07:41.830
They are very big and they die in just a couple
million years.

00:07:41.830 --> 00:07:45.069
So they never move outside the plane of the
Milky Way.

00:07:45.069 --> 00:07:51.380
So, as I fly out, the dots that I turned on
there is the locations of what’s called

00:07:51.380 --> 00:07:52.960
“star formation regions.”

00:07:52.960 --> 00:07:55.720
Most people know Orion, right?

00:07:55.720 --> 00:07:57.730
Everybody loves Orion.

00:07:57.730 --> 00:08:02.449
Orion is the closest star-forming region to
the Earth.

00:08:02.449 --> 00:08:07.919
And so I pulled out, part of why I think this
phenomenal—notice these streaks.

00:08:07.919 --> 00:08:10.539
I kind of call them fingers of God.

00:08:10.539 --> 00:08:13.879
And those are marking for you clumps.

00:08:13.879 --> 00:08:18.449
These are where star-forming regions are located.

00:08:18.449 --> 00:08:23.479
And part of—I’m going to run it again—and
as you fall out, what you’ll see is, okay,

00:08:23.479 --> 00:08:27.650
we all know, that image of the galaxy you
just saw, we didn’t take that picture.

00:08:27.650 --> 00:08:32.800
Voyager is kind of the farthest thing we ever
sent and it’s barely left the solar system.

00:08:32.800 --> 00:08:35.280
So we’ve never taken a picture of the galaxy.

00:08:35.280 --> 00:08:39.690
But what we’re able to do in this map, and
as I fly out here the second time, what you’ll

00:08:39.690 --> 00:08:44.560
see is the locations of those star-forming
regions.

00:08:44.560 --> 00:08:51.800
Those locations of these hot, O and B stars
are telling you the shape of the Milky Way

00:08:51.800 --> 00:08:52.800
galaxy.

00:08:52.800 --> 00:08:57.410
It’s been heavily debated what the shape
of the Milky Way galaxy is.

00:08:57.410 --> 00:08:58.930
Does it have spiral arms?

00:08:58.930 --> 00:09:02.029
I mean, we think so, we’re in a spiral galaxy.

00:09:02.029 --> 00:09:04.470
What do those spiral arms look like?

00:09:04.470 --> 00:09:09.590
You can now use these stars as a map to try
and get to that structure.

00:09:09.590 --> 00:09:13.970
And part of why at this point in the video
that I’m sort of zooming around, and you’ll

00:09:13.970 --> 00:09:18.040
see I turn on this image of the galaxy and
turn it off.

00:09:18.040 --> 00:09:22.990
As you blink on and blink off, what you’re
seeing is gaps.

00:09:22.990 --> 00:09:24.670
And non-gaps.

00:09:24.670 --> 00:09:30.740
Which look like you’re basically getting
the structure of the spiral galaxy out from

00:09:30.740 --> 00:09:36.620
this very simple thing of just mapping the
hottest stars in the galaxy.

00:09:36.620 --> 00:09:40.940
Okay, next video I’m going to show you,
and this is my favorite one—you’re not

00:09:40.940 --> 00:09:43.580
supposed to have favorites, but I have favorites.

00:09:43.580 --> 00:09:45.950
So, this is my favorite one.

00:09:45.950 --> 00:09:48.420
This is what I call the solar neighborhood
flybys.

00:09:48.420 --> 00:09:53.769
This is something that I’ve wanted to do,
just something I’ve always wanted to do.

00:09:53.769 --> 00:10:01.709
If you know how stars are moving and you know
how far away they are, you can look at their

00:10:01.709 --> 00:10:03.760
trajectories.

00:10:03.760 --> 00:10:10.300
We are stuck in this static view, like I mentioned,
of what the galaxy looks like right now, what

00:10:10.300 --> 00:10:13.360
the nearby stars look like right now.

00:10:13.360 --> 00:10:20.589
But once Gaia showed up with all of these
motions and distances, we can turn time on

00:10:20.589 --> 00:10:26.100
and you can see—are these the stars that
have always been the closest stars to us?

00:10:26.100 --> 00:10:28.470
Did we ever have a flyby?

00:10:28.470 --> 00:10:34.680
Did another star come sweeping through our
solar system and knock a bunch of stuff around?

00:10:34.680 --> 00:10:41.480
Kicking comets and asteroids from the Kuyper
Belt and the Ort Cloud, the asteroid belt,

00:10:41.480 --> 00:10:43.490
in towards the inner solar system.

00:10:43.490 --> 00:10:47.100
Well, we can turn time on on this video.

00:10:47.100 --> 00:10:49.960
So this is a cartoon version of the sun.

00:10:49.960 --> 00:10:52.700
This is rendered with software we have here
called Open Space.

00:10:52.700 --> 00:10:56.930
So, again, in the corner here, it’s telling
you what software I’m rendering this with.

00:10:56.930 --> 00:11:01.620
And these are all stars that you cannot see
with your eye.

00:11:01.620 --> 00:11:04.910
Because your eye can’t really detect anything
but the brightest stars.

00:11:04.910 --> 00:11:09.800
And so I’m going to turn time on right now
and it’s going to go over a couple of million

00:11:09.800 --> 00:11:10.800
years.

00:11:10.800 --> 00:11:15.589
So you’re going to watch your future.

00:11:15.589 --> 00:11:22.090
And don’t be scared, but kind of be scared.

00:11:22.090 --> 00:11:26.529
This is a lot of stuff going on here.

00:11:26.529 --> 00:11:33.860
So, what you’re seeing—again, don’t
be scared, but be scared—that all of the

00:11:33.860 --> 00:11:36.600
stars around you are moving.

00:11:36.600 --> 00:11:37.959
Everything is moving.

00:11:37.959 --> 00:11:41.700
And you don’t know, though—are they moving
toward you?

00:11:41.700 --> 00:11:43.440
Are they moving away from you?

00:11:43.440 --> 00:11:48.889
What this video is showing is mostly—sorry—mostly
the stars motion through the galaxy.

00:11:48.889 --> 00:11:54.280
You’re watching the stars have their trajectory
in the plane of the galaxy.

00:11:54.280 --> 00:11:58.550
But notice some of them are flying closer
than others.

00:11:58.550 --> 00:12:01.910
And what was an immediate thing that came
out of this—this was actually something

00:12:01.910 --> 00:12:07.650
that we knew from Hipparcos, but we know it
so much better now, is that in—this another

00:12:07.650 --> 00:12:13.600
little movie that I’ll show you close in—in
1.2 million years, there’s a star called

00:12:13.600 --> 00:12:14.709
Gliese 710.

00:12:14.709 --> 00:12:19.700
It’s about 60% the mass of the sun.

00:12:19.700 --> 00:12:25.029
And it’s going to come within the Ort Cloud,
which is that cloud of debris that I’m flying

00:12:25.029 --> 00:12:26.290
you towards right now.

00:12:26.290 --> 00:12:31.579
You can see the star right there.

00:12:31.579 --> 00:12:35.950
You can come in past the glare of the sun,
past the Kuyper Belt into the Earth.

00:12:35.950 --> 00:12:38.360
And in 1.2 million years, look out.

00:12:38.360 --> 00:12:40.170
Who knows if we’ll still be around.

00:12:40.170 --> 00:12:44.230
But if are, Gliese 710 is doing a flyby.

00:12:44.230 --> 00:12:50.060
And, when it does, it looks like it’ll kick
around a bunch of stuff in the Ort Cloud.

00:12:50.060 --> 00:12:53.730
When it does that, it sends stuff into the
inner solar system.

00:12:53.730 --> 00:12:55.940
Now, okay, I’m not trying to scare you.

00:12:55.940 --> 00:13:04.639
But that is an absolutely important of understanding
solar systems, to know what is the dynamic

00:13:04.639 --> 00:13:06.750
nature of how things move.

00:13:06.750 --> 00:13:10.000
And just one other thing on this, too.

00:13:10.000 --> 00:13:12.010
I’m going to run this again.

00:13:12.010 --> 00:13:14.320
How many people have heard of Oumuamua?

00:13:14.320 --> 00:13:16.410
Anybody hear of Oumuamua?

00:13:16.410 --> 00:13:19.550
Couple of shouts, one or two.

00:13:19.550 --> 00:13:23.149
Oumuamua is this object that was a recent
visitor.

00:13:23.149 --> 00:13:27.000
So I’m just going to turn this on to continually
scare you.

00:13:27.000 --> 00:13:35.850
Oumuamua is this piece of debris, it looks
like, that came from a different solar system.

00:13:35.850 --> 00:13:38.300
It flew through our solar system very recently.

00:13:38.300 --> 00:13:40.630
It was discovered a year ago.

00:13:40.630 --> 00:13:44.829
And we caught it, it’s on what’s called
a hyperbolic orbit, which means it’s not

00:13:44.829 --> 00:13:46.830
bound to our own sun.

00:13:46.830 --> 00:13:47.830
Flew right out.

00:13:47.830 --> 00:13:54.370
Now, using the data like this, astronomers,
it was just last week, used this exact thing

00:13:54.370 --> 00:13:59.140
that I’m showing you to trace back where
Oumuamua might have come from.

00:13:59.140 --> 00:14:01.700
Now, we’re not sure that it’s right.

00:14:01.700 --> 00:14:04.260
I mean, that’s also the other aspect of
this.

00:14:04.260 --> 00:14:08.449
We’re not positive we got all the velocities
and the positions correct.

00:14:08.449 --> 00:14:15.470
But never before in time have we been able
to even take the step towards this.

00:14:15.470 --> 00:14:20.269
Where you could trace back the motion of an
object that came from a completely different

00:14:20.269 --> 00:14:25.990
solar system and try and find its host, to
find where it came from.

00:14:25.990 --> 00:14:32.720
An ejected piece of garbage from some other
star that just passed through here.

00:14:32.720 --> 00:14:34.480
And we studied it.

00:14:34.480 --> 00:14:39.040
And now we used this kind of thing to trace
back where it might have come from.

00:14:39.040 --> 00:14:41.860
So, that should excite you.

00:14:41.860 --> 00:14:49.709
That is the science on the horizon of what
we’re able to do in the nearby solar neighborhood.

00:14:49.709 --> 00:14:54.190
Another thing that we can do with this gigantic
dataset—this is something that I worked

00:14:54.190 --> 00:14:59.380
on heavily—is look for objects that move
