00:21:12.300 --> 00:21:14.870
So here comes Kepler into this field of view.

00:21:14.870 --> 00:21:19.830
Notice the blue circles here which are marking
for you the location of planets around stars.

00:21:19.830 --> 00:21:23.710
It’s very close to the sun.

00:21:23.710 --> 00:21:27.120
And that’s because a lot of those, we’re
just looking at the brightest stars using

00:21:27.120 --> 00:21:29.920
a technique called the radio velocity method.

00:21:29.920 --> 00:21:34.530
Kepler used what’s called the transiting
method, which means you stared at a field

00:21:34.530 --> 00:21:40.190
